Quotes from Clausius 1851 en, \cite{clausius1850, clausius1850en, clausius1850fr}

ch7
The steam-engine having furnished us with a means of converting heat into a motive power, and our thoughts being thereby led to regard a certain quantity of work as an equivalent for the amount of heat expended in its production, the idea of establishing theoretically some fixed relation between a quantity of heat and the quantity of work which it can possibly produce, from which relation conclusions regarding the nature of heat itself might be deduced, naturally presents itself.
\cite{clausius1850, clausius1850en, clausius1850fr}

ch1
I am not, however, sure that the assertion, that in the production of work a loss of heat never occurs, is sufficiently established by experiment. Perhaps the contrary might be asserted with greater justice [...]
\cite{clausius1850, clausius1850en, clausius1850fr}

ch1
If we assume that heat, like matter, cannot be lessened in quantity, we must also assume that it cannot be increased ; but it is almost impossible to explain the ascension of temperature brought about by friction otherwise than by assuming an actual increase of heat.
It might be remarked further, that many facts have lately transpired which tend to overthrow the hypothesis that heat is itself a body, and to prove that it consists in a motion of the ultimate particles of bodies. If this be so, the general principles of mechanics may be applied to heat ; this motion may be converted into work, the loss of /vis viva/ in each particular case being proportional to the quantity of work produced.
\cite{clausius1850, clausius1850en, clausius1850fr}

ch1
These circumstances [...] pressingly demand a comparison between heat and work, to be undertaken with reference to the divergent assumption that the production of work is not only due to an alternation in the /distribution/ of heat, but to an actual /consumption/ thereof ; and inversely, that by the consumption of work heat may be /produced/. 
\cite{clausius1850, clausius1850en, clausius1850fr}

ch4, ch5
Gases exhibit in their deportment, particularly as regards the relations of volume, temperature and pressure, expressed by the laws of Mariotte and Gay-Lussac, so much regularity as to lead us to the notion that the mutual attraction of the particles [,] which takes place in solid and fluid bodies [,] is in their case annulled ; so that while with solids and fluids the heat necessary to effect an expansion has to contend with both an inner and an outer resistance, the latter only is effective in the case of gases.
\cite{clausius1850, clausius1850en, clausius1850fr}

ch4
[...] we obtain the proposition, /when a permanent gas expands at a constant temperature, it absorbs only as much heat as is necessary to the exterior work produved by the expansion/ ; a proposition which is probably true for all gases in the same degree as the law of Mariotte and Gay-Lussac.
\cite{clausius1850, clausius1850en, clausius1850fr}

------------ halfway through, switched to French version directly

ch7
Ce maximum [de travail] jouit en effet de la propriété que, par sa /consommation/, on peut faire passer du corps froid B au corps chaud A la même quantité de chaleur que celle qui a passé de A en B pour sa /production/.
\cite{clausius1850, clausius1850en, clausius1850fr}

ch7
D’après cela, nous pouvons []nous[] regarder comme fondé /théoriquement/ à admettre la première partie de l’hypothèse de Carnot, qui est du reste la partie vraiment essentielle, et à en faire un second principe, que nous joindrons à celui qui vient d’être établi ; l’exactitude de ces principes sera maintes fois vérifiée par les résultats, comme nous le verrons bientôt.
\cite{clausius1850, clausius1850en, clausius1850fr}


